Let's create a simple feedback form using HTML, CSS, and JavaScript. We'll focus on the client-side scripting part, which will handle user input and submission.

**HTML Structure**

First, let's create the basic HTML structure for our feedback form:
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Feedback Form</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="style.css">
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Feedback Form</h1>
    <form id="feedback-form">
        <label for="name">Name:</label>
        <input type="text" id="name" name="name"><br><br>
        <label for="email">Email:</label>
        <input type="email" id="email" name="email"><br><br>
        <label for="feedback">Feedback:</label>
        <textarea id="feedback" name="feedback"></textarea><br><br>
        <button type="submit">Submit</button>
    </form>
    <div id="result"></div>

    <script src="script.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
```
This HTML structure includes:

* A form with three fields: name, email, and feedback (a textarea).
* A submit button to send the form data.
* A div element to display the result of the form submission.

**CSS Styling**

Next, let's add some basic CSS styling to make the form look more visually appealing:
```css
/* style.css */

body {
    font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
    background-color: #f2f2f2;
}

form {
    width: 50%;
    margin: 40px auto;
    padding: 20px;
    border: 1px solid #ccc;
    border-radius: 10px;
    box-shadow: 0 0 10px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);
}

label {
    display: block;
    margin-bottom: 10px;
}

input, textarea {
    width: 100%;
    padding: 10px;
    margin-bottom: 20px;
    border: 1px solid #ccc;
    border-radius: 5px;
}

button[type="submit"] {
    background-color: #4CAF50;
    color: #fff;
    padding: 10px 20px;
    border: none;
    border-radius: 5px;
    cursor: pointer;
}

button[type="submit"]:hover {
    background-color: #3e8e41;
}
```
This CSS styling adds basic layout, typography, and visual effects to the form.

**JavaScript Scripting**

Now, let's add the JavaScript code to handle user input and submission:
```javascript
// script.js

const form = document.getElementById('feedback-form');
const resultDiv = document.getElementById('result');

form.addEventListener('submit', (e) => {
    e.preventDefault();

    const name = document.getElementById('name').value;
    const email = document.getElementById('email').value;
    const feedback = document.getElementById('feedback').value;

    if (name && email && feedback) {
        const formData = {
            name,
            email,
            feedback,
        };

        // Send the form data to a server-side script (e.g., PHP, Node.js)
        // For demonstration purposes, we'll just log the form data to the console
        console.log(formData);

        // Display a success message
        resultDiv.textContent = 'Thank you for your feedback!';
        resultDiv.style.color = 'green';
    } else {
        // Display an error message
        resultDiv.textContent = 'Please fill out all fields.';
        resultDiv.style.color = 'red';
    }
});
```
This JavaScript code:

* Gets references to the form and result div elements.
* Adds an event listener to the form's submit event.
* Prevents the default form submission behavior.
* Retrieves the values of the name, email, and feedback fields.
* Checks if all fields are filled out.
* If all fields are filled out, logs the form data to the console and displays a success message.
* If any fields are empty, displays an error message.

**Putting it all together**

Save the HTML, CSS, and JavaScript code in separate files (e.g., `index.html`, `style.css`, and `script.js`) and open the `index.html` file in a web browser. Fill out the form, submit it, and observe the result.

This is a basic example of how to create a feedback form using HTML, CSS, and JavaScript. You can customize and extend this code to suit your needs.

