Let's walk through a complete example of creating a feedback form that captures and stores user input on the server-side using Node.js and a database.

**Server-Side Setup**

First, we'll set up a basic Node.js server using Express.js to handle form submissions and store the data in a database.

**Step 1: Install Dependencies**

Create a new project directory and run the following command to install the required dependencies:
```bash
npm init -y
npm install express body-parser mongoose
```
**Step 2: Create a Server**

Create a new file called `server.js` and add the following code:
```javascript
const express = require('express');
const bodyParser = require('body-parser');
const mongoose = require('mongoose');

const app = express();
const port = 3000;

mongoose.connect('mongodb://localhost/feedback', { useNewUrlParser: true, useUnifiedTopology: true });

const feedbackSchema = new mongoose.Schema({
  name: String,
  email: String,
  feedback: String,
});

const Feedback = mongoose.model('Feedback', feedbackSchema);

app.use(bodyParser.urlencoded({ extended: true }));
app.use(bodyParser.json());

app.post('/feedback', (req, res) => {
  const feedback = new Feedback(req.body);
  feedback.save((err, data) => {
    if (err) {
      console.error(err);
      res.status(500).send({ message: 'Error saving feedback' });
    } else {
      res.send({ message: 'Feedback saved successfully' });
    }
  });
});

app.listen(port, () => {
  console.log(`Server listening on port ${port}`);
});
```
This code sets up an Express.js server that listens on port 3000 and connects to a MongoDB database. It defines a `Feedback` model using Mongoose and creates a route to handle form submissions.

**Step 3: Create a Form**

Create a new file called `index.html` and add the following code:
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title>Feedback Form</title>
</head>
<body>
  <h1>Feedback Form</h1>
  <form id="feedback-form" action="/feedback" method="post">
    <label for="name">Name:</label>
    <input type="text" id="name" name="name"><br><br>
    <label for="email">Email:</label>
    <input type="email" id="email" name="email"><br><br>
    <label for="feedback">Feedback:</label>
    <textarea id="feedback" name="feedback"></textarea><br><br>
    <button type="submit">Submit</button>
  </form>

  <script src="script.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
```
This code creates a basic form that submits to the `/feedback` route on the server.

**Step 4: Handle Form Submissions**

Create a new file called `script.js` and add the following code:
```javascript
const form = document.getElementById('feedback-form');

form.addEventListener('submit', (e) => {
  e.preventDefault();
  const formData = new FormData(form);
  fetch('/feedback', {
    method: 'POST',
    body: formData,
  })
    .then((response) => response.json())
    .then((data) => console.log(data))
    .catch((error) => console.error(error));
});
```
This code adds an event listener to the form's submit event and sends the form data to the `/feedback` route on the server using the Fetch API.

**Putting it all together**

Save all the files and run the server using the following command:
```bash
node server.js
```
Open a web browser and navigate to `http://localhost:3000`. Fill out the form and submit it. The form data should be saved to the MongoDB database.

**Viewing the Data**

To view the saved data, you can use a tool like MongoDB Compass or Robo 3T to connect to the database and query the `feedback` collection.

This is a basic example of how to create a feedback form that captures and stores user input on the server-side using Node.js and a database. You can customize and extend this code to suit your needs.

